{"title_page": "List of aviation awards", "text_new": "[[File:Weymannissy.jpeg|thumb|Weymann, competitor in the Michelin Grand Prix 1910, shortly after departure from [[Issy-les-Moulineaux]] ]]\nThis '''list of aviation awards''' is an index to articles about notable awards given in the field of [[aviation]]. It includes a list of awards for winners of competitions or records, a list of awards by the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]], various other awards and list of aviation halls of fame.\n\n{{Dynamic list}}\n\n==Competitions and records==\n\nAwards for speed and distance of flights were popular in the early days of aviation, and some continue today.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:6em;\"|Country !! Award !! Sponsor !! Given for\n|-\n| United States || [[Barringer Trophy]] || [[Soaring Society of America]] || longest distance soaring flight other than those flown at the US National Contest<ref>{{cite journal|title=Barringer Trophy|journal=Soaring|date=March\u2013April 1948|volume=12|issue=3\u20134|pages=17}}</ref>\n|-\n| United States || [[Bendix Trophy]] || [[Bendix Corporation]] || Transcontinental, point-to-point race<ref> [http://www.airracinghistory.freeola.com/Between%20the%20wars(2).htm \"The Bendix Trophy\"], ''Air Racing History'', retrieved January 6, 2006</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20060211160117/http://www.aeromuseum.org/Articles/July04/QuestForSpeed.htm \"The Quest for Speed Bendix Air Races 1931 to 1949\"] From Air Trails, September 1950</ref>\n|-\n| France || [[Coupe Deutsch de la Meurthe]] || [[A\u00e9ro-Club de France]] || Speed trial for powered aircraft over a distance of 200 kilometres, to be flown as an outward leg of 100 km followed by a return to the starting point<ref>[http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6551284g/f7.image.r=Deutsch%20de%20la%20Meurthe Bulletin Officiel de l'A\u0117ro-Club de France] [[l'A\u0117rophile]], March 1906, p.71</ref><ref>{{cite |journal=Flight |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1919/1919%20-%201366.html |title=Coupe Henry Deutsch de l a Meurthe |volume=XI |number=564|date=16 October 1919 |page= 1368}}</ref>\n|-\n| United Kingdom || [[Daily Mail aviation prizes]] || ''[[Daily Mail]]'' newspaper || Various competitions<ref>[http://www.flightglobal.com/PDFArchive/View/1913/1913%20-%200958.html \"Direct initiative of Lord Northcliffe] Flight\" PDF Archive, 6 September 1913</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Such |first1=Colin |title=The Daily Mail's Sponsorship of British Pioneer Aviation |url=https://www.warwickandwarwick.com/resources/articles-library/the-daily-mails-sponsorship-of-british-pioneer-aviation |website=Warwick & Warwick |accessdate=13 August 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| International || [[De la Vaulx Medal]] || [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]] || Holders of recognized absolute world aviation records<ref>{{citation |accessdate=2020-02-14 |url=https://www.fai.org/awards |title=FAI Awards : The De La Vaulx Medal |publisher=FAI }}</ref>\n|-\n| United States || [[Dole Air Race]] || [[James Dole]] || Air race across the Pacific Ocean from northern [[California]] to the [[Territory of Hawaii]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Dole Derby|url=http://hawaii.gov/hawaiiaviation/aviation-photos/1920-1929/dole-derby/ha_photo_album_view?b_start:int=0&-C=|accessdate=23 August 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| France || [[Femina Cup]] || ''Femina'' (French magazine) ||  Woman who, by sunset on 31 December each year, had made the longest flight, in time and distance, without landing<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womeninaerospacehistory.com/tag/coupe-femina/|title=22 December 1910: H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Dutrieu|last=|first=|date=22 December 2015|website=Women in Aerospace History|publisher=Smithsonian|access-date=7 December 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| United States|| [[Gordon Bennett Trophy (aeroplanes)]] || [[James Gordon Bennett Jr. ]] || Fastest time over a measured distance (time trial)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.esparacing.com/sport_pilot/air_racing_history.htm |title=Air Racing History |publisher=ESPA Racing |accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.century-of-flight.net/Aviation%20history/up%20to%20WW%201/Reims%20Race.htm |title=Reims Air Race |publisher=Century of Flight |accessdate=31 March 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n| United States || [[Hearst Transcontinental Prize]] || [[William Randolph Hearst]] || First aviator to fly coast to coast across the United States, in either direction, in fewer than 30 days from start to finish. The prize expired in November 1911 without a winner.<ref>{{cite news |title=Flier, Seeking to Reach San Francisco, Lands at Calicoon Late in the Afternoon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1911/09/15/archives/ward-138-miles-nearer-pacific-flier-seeking-to-reach-san-francisco.html |quote=James J. Ward, who left New York for San Francisco Wednesday, flying for the W.R. Hearst $50,000 prize for a transcontinental flight, reached Callicoon, N.Y., a few miles from here, at 4:35 o'clock this afternoon. He covered 59 1-10 miles in 57 minutes, having left Middletown, N.Y., at 3:38 o'clock. |work=[[New York Times]] |date= September 15, 1911|accessdate=2010-11-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Ward Quits Coast Flight. Comes to Grief at Addison  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1911/09/23/archives/ward-quits-coast-flight-comes-to-grief-at-addison-rodgers-at-elmira.html |quote=|work=[[New York Times]] |date=September 23, 1911 |accessdate=2010-11-26 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://centennialchallenges.nasa.gov/documents/cc_ilc_paper_2005-09-08.pdf\n|title=Prize Competitions and NASA's Centennial Challenges Program|year=2005|publisher=[[NASA]]|accessdate=2007-09-23 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070703112137/http://centennialchallenges.nasa.gov/documents/cc_ilc_paper_2005-09-08.pdf <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-07-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| Germany || [[Hindenburg Cup]] || [[Paul von Hindenburg]] || Achievements in powered flight<ref>{{citation|author=Evelyn Zegenhagen|title=\"Schneidige deutsche M\u00e4del\": Fliegerinnen zwischen 1918 und 1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RMuEi7E_N_sC&pg=PA134|year=2007|publisher=Wallstein Verlag|isbn=978-3-8353-0179-5|page=134}}</ref>\n|-\n| United States || [[Igor I. Sikorsky Human Powered Helicopter Competition]] || [[American Helicopter Society (AHS) International]] || First human powered helicopter to meet a set of extremely challenging flight requirements<ref>AHS International, [http://vtol.org/awards-and-contests/human-powered-helicopter/hph-rules Human Powered Helicopter Regulations], retrieved July 12, 2013.</ref>\n|-\n| International || [[Lilienthal Gliding Medal]] || [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration A\u00e9ronautique Internationale]] || Remarkable performance in gliding, or eminent services to the sport of gliding over a long period of time<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ssa.org/myhome.asp?mbr=7262842059&show=blog&id=812#Lilienthal|title= SSA Awards and SSA Recognized Awards - International Awards|publisher= Soaring Society of America |accessdate= 2011-02-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|International\n|[[Edison Awards]]\n|[[Edison Awards]]\n|Honoring excellence in new product and service development, marketing, human-centered design and innovation\n|-\n| United States || [[Mackay Trophy]] || [[United States Air Force]] || Most meritorious flight of the year<ref>[http://www.nasm.si.edu/research/aero/trophy/mackay.cfm Smithsonian Mackay Trophy Page] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060901071348/http://www.nasm.si.edu/research/aero/trophy/mackay.cfm |date=2006-09-01 }}</ref>\n|-\n| France || [[Michelin Cup]] || [[Michelin]] || Various long distance flight competition<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[l'A\u00e9rophile]]|url= http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k6550620m/f125.image.r=Michelin.langEN|page=115|language=French|date=March 1908|title=La Coupe d'Aviation et les Prix d'Aviation Michelin}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1911/1911%20-%200205.html|journal=[[Flight International|Flight]]|date=11 March 1911|title =Renaux wins the Michelin Puy de Dome Prize|page=207}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Flight International|Flight]]|url=http://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1909/1909%20-%200181.html|title=Prize Treatise on Aerial Navigation|date=27 March 1909|page=183}}</ref>\n|-\n| United States || [[Orteig Prize]] || [[Raymond Orteig]] || First Allied aviator(s) to fly non-stop from New York City to Paris or vice versa<ref>{{cite book | author=Bak, Richard |title=The Big Jump - Lindbergh and the Great Atlantic Air Race | url=https://archive.org/details/bigjumplindbergh0000bakr | url-access=registration | location=Hoboken | publisher= John Wiley & Sons| year=2011 | isbn=978-0-471-47752-5|pages=28-29 }}</ref> \n|-\n| United States || [[Richard C. du Pont Memorial Trophy]] || [[Soaring Society of America]] || Winner of U.S. National Open Class Soaring Championship<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061025204042/http://soaring.aerobatics.ws/Awards/dupont.html Soaring Society of America Richard C. du Pont Memorial details]</ref>\n|-\n| France || [[Schneider Trophy]] || [[Jacques Schneider]] || Winner of a race for seaplanes and flying boats (see also [[Schneider Trophy aircraft]])<ref>Eves, Edward. ''The Schneider Trophy Story''. Shrewsbury, UK: Airlife Publishing Ltd., 2001. {{ISBN|1-84037-257-5}} pp=240ff</ref>\n|-\n| United States || [[Thompson Trophy]] || [[Thompson Products]] || The race was 10 miles (16 km) long with 50-foot-high (15 m) pylons marking the turns, and emphasized low altitude flying and maneuverability at high speeds<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051128072503/http://www.centennialofflight.gov/essay/Explorers_Record_Setters_and_Daredevils/trophies/EX10.htm The Major Trophy Races of the Golden Age of Air Racing]</ref><ref>[http://www.airracinghistory.freeola.com/Thompson%20Trophy.htm Thompson Trophy] on Air Racing History site</ref>\n|}\n\n==Society of Experimental Test Pilots awards==\n\nThe [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]], an international organization based in the United States, offers or has offered various awards.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Award  !! Given for\n|-\n| [[European Flight Test Safety Award]] || Individuals who made significant contributions in the area of safety within flight testing<ref>{{citation |accessdate=2020-02-14 |url=http://flighttestsafety.org/awards |title=Gerard Guillamaud European Flight Test Safety Award |publisher=Flight Test Safety Committee}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Friend of the Society of Experimental Test Pilots Award]] || Exceptional and notable contribution to the operation and the objectives of the Society of Experimental Test Pilots<ref>{{cite web |title=Friend of the Society Award Criteria |url=http://www.setp.org/criteria/friend-of-the-society.html |date= |work= |publisher=Society of Experimental Test Pilots |accessdate=January 15, 2010}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Herman R. Salmon Award]] || Most outstanding technical paper published in ''Cockpit'' magazine<ref>{{cite web |title=Herman R. Salmon Technical Publications Award Criteria |url=http://www.setp.org/criteria/herman-r-salmon-technical-publications-award.html |date= |work= |publisher=Society of Experimental Test Pilots |accessdate=September 24, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Iven C. Kincheloe Award]] || Outstanding professional accomplishment in the conduct of flight testing<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/39952492/the_evening_news/ |title=Kincheloe's Name Still Honored|newspaper=The Evening News|location=Sault Sainte Marie|date=May 7, 1970|page=8|via=Newspapers.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[James H. Doolittle Award]] || Outstanding accomplishment in technical management or engineering achievement in aerospace technology<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.setp.org/criteria/james-h-doolittle-award.html |title=James H. Doolittle Award Criteria |publisher=Setp.org |date= |accessdate=2010-09-29}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Ray E. Tenhoff Award]] || Most outstanding technical paper presented at the annual Society of Experimental Test Pilots Symposium<ref>{{cite web |title=Ray E. Tenhoff Award Criteria |url=http://www.setp.org/criteria/ray-e-tenhoff-award.html |work= |publisher=Society of Experimental Test Pilots |accessdate=September 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Ray E. Tenhoff Award |url= |date= September 27, 2008 |series=52nd Awards Banquet|publisher=Privately Published |accessdate= }}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tony LeVier Flight Test Safety Award]] || People who have significantly contributed to the safety of flight test operations<ref>{{citation |accessdate=2020-02-14 |url=http://flighttestsafety.org/awards |title=Tony LeVier Flight Test Safety Award |publisher=Flight Test Safety Committee}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other awards==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!style=\"width:6em;\"|Country !! Award !! Sponsor !! Given for\n|-\n| United Stares || [[A. Leo Stevens Parachute Medal]] || [[National Air Races]] || Contributions to parachute design and techniques<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parafame.org/history_of_leo_stevens_award.htm |title=History of the Leo Stevens Award |accessdate=2010-12-26 |quote=The Leo Stevens Award is the major parachuting award in the United States. ... |publisher=[[Museum of History in Granite]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aero.com/publications/parachutes/9601/pc0196.htm |title=The A. Leo Stevens Parachute Medal |accessdate=2010-12-27 |publisher=Aero.com |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20101125063836/http://aero.com/publications/parachutes/9601/pc0196.htm |archivedate=2010-11-25 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|-\n| Brazil || [[Order of Aeronautical Merit (Brazil)|Order of Aeronautical Merit]] || [[Brazilian Air Force]] || Distinguished service and exceptional contributions to the Brazilian Air Force<ref>{{cite web | last =Robertson | first =Megan C. | title =The Federative Republic of Brazil: Order of Aeronautical Merit | work =Medals of the World | publisher = 